### D365FO Integration Patterns — sample requests
### Replace the placeholders below, then run with the VS Code REST Client
### extension (or import into Postman/Insomnia).

@gateway = https://<your-apim-name>.azure-api.net
@key     = <your-subscription-key>

### API 2 — Fake REST service: get a post (no D365 dependency)
GET {{gateway}}/fake/posts/1
Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key: {{key}}

### API 2 — Fake REST service: list users
GET {{gateway}}/fake/users
Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key: {{key}}

### API 3 — Customers: REST -> OData transformation (happy path)
POST {{gateway}}/d365/customers/search
Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key: {{key}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "customerAccount": "DE-001" }

### API 3 — Customers: validation error (missing customerAccount -> 400)
POST {{gateway}}/d365/customers/search
Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key: {{key}}
Content-Type: application/json

{}

### API 1 — WHS Release to Warehouse (D365FO custom service + transformation)
### The policy maps this friendly JSON into the D365FO _contract shape
### (enum -> int, booleans -> NoYes 0/1). Without a packed query over
### InventTransferTable, D365FO returns a validation error (expected in the demo).
POST {{gateway}}/d365/whs/autoReleaseTransferOrders
Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key: {{key}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "quantitySpecification": "All",
  "allowPartiallyReleased": false,
  "groupIntoMultipleReleases": false,
  "packedQuery": ""
}
